  \point (o) at (0,0);
  \draw[vector,seq-red] (o) -- node[at end, left=1mm] {$\vec{-6 4}$} (x);
  \point[seq-blue, "$\displaystyle-\frac{10}{13}\vec{3 2}$" {below right,xshift=-2mm,yshift=2mm,seq-blue}]
    (p) at (${-2.5/(1.5*1.5+1)}*(1.5,1)$);
  \draw (p) -- (x);
  \pic[draw] {right angle=(x)--(p)--(o)};
\end{tikzpicture}

p.me:
x_L = \frac{x\cdot u}{u\cdot u}\,u = \frac{2+3-1}{1+1+1}\vec{-1 1 1} = \frac{4}{3}\vec{-1 1 1}
\qquad
x_{L^\perp} = x - x_L = \frac 13\vec{-2 5 -7}.

statement.p:
Let

  W = \left\{\vec{x_1 x_2 x_3}\bigm|x_1 - 2x_2 = x_3\right\}
  \sptxt{and}
  x = \vec{1 1 1}.

Compute x_W.

solution.p:
The columns of B are T(e_1) = (e_1)_L and T(e_2) = (e_2)_L.  We have

  \left.
  \begin{split}
  (e_1)_L \amp= \frac{u\cdot e_1}{u\cdot u}\,u
  = \frac{3}{13}\vec{3 2} \\
  (e_2)_L \amp= \frac{u\cdot e_2}{u\cdot u}\,u
  = \frac{2}{13}\vec{3 2}
  \end{split}
  \right\} \quad\implies\quad
  B = \frac 1{13}\mat{9 6; 6 4}.

subsection.p:
In the previous , we could have used the fact that

  \left\{\vec{1 0 -1},\;\vec{1 1 0}\right\}

forms a basis for W, so that

  T(x) = x_W = \bigl[A(A^TA)\inv A^T\bigr]x
  \sptxt{for}
  A = \mat{1 1; 0 1; -1 0}

by the .  In this case, we have already expressed T as a matrix transformation with matrix A(A^TA)\inv A^T.  See this .

remark.p:
As we saw in this , if you are willing to compute bases for W and W^\perp, then this provides a third way of finding the standard matrix B for projection onto W: indeed, if \{v_1,v_2,\ldots,v_m\} is a basis for W and \{v_{m+1},v_{m+2},\ldots,v_n\} is a basis for W^\perp, then

  B = \mat{| | ,, |; v_1 v_1 \cdots, v_n; | | ,, |}
  \mat{
  1 \cdots, 0 0 \cdots, 0;
  \vdots, \ddots, \vdots, \vdots, \ddots, \vdots;
  0 \cdots, 1 0 \cdots, 0;
  0 \cdots, 0 0 \cdots, 0;
  \vdots, \ddots, \vdots, \vdots, \ddots, \vdots;
  0 \cdots, 0 0 \cdots, 0}
  \mat{| | ,, |; v_1 v_1 \cdots, v_n; | | ,, |}\inv,

where the middle matrix in the product is the diagonal matrix with m ones and n-m zeros on the diagonal.  However, since you already have a basis for W, it is faster to multiply out the expression A(A^TA)\inv A^T as in the .

        Let W be a subspace of \R^n, and let x be a vector in \R^n.  The reflection of x over W is defined to be the vector

          \refl_W(x) = x - 2x_{W^\perp}.

        In other words, to find \refl_W(x) one starts at x, then moves to x-x_{W^\perp} = x_W, then continues in the same direction one more time, to end on the opposite side of W.

\begin{tikzpicture}[thin border nodes]
  \draw[seq-violet] (-3,-2) -- node[below right, very near start] {$W$} (3,2);
  \coordinate (x) at (-3,2);
  \coordinate (o) at (0,0);
  \draw[vector,seq-red] (o) -- node[auto,swap] {$x$} (x);
  \point[seq-blue, "$x_W$" {seq-blue, below, yshift=-2mm}] (p) at (${-2.5/(1.5*1.5+1)}*(1.5,1)$);
  \coordinate (p2) at ($-1*(x)+2*(p)$);
  \draw[vector, seq-green] (x) -- node[below left] {$-x_{W^\perp}$} (p);
  \draw[vector, seq-green] (p) -- node[below left] {$-x_{W^\perp}$} ($-1*(x)+2*(p)$);
  \draw[vector, seq-green] (p) -- node[below left] {$-x_{W^\perp}$} (p2);
  \pic[draw] {right angle=(o)--(p)--(p2)};
  \draw[vector, seq-orange] (o) -- node[right=2pt] {$\refl_W(x)$} (p2);
  \point at (o);
\end{tikzpicture}

        Since x_{W^\perp} = x - x_W, we also have

          \refl_W(x) = x - 2(x - x_W) = 2x_W - x.

        We leave it to the reader to check using the definition that:


\refl_W\circ\refl_W = \Id_{\R^n}.

The 1-eigenspace of \refl_W is W, and the -1-eigenspace of \refl_W is W^\perp.

\refl_W is similar to the diagonal matrix with m = \dim(W) ones on the diagonal and n-m negative ones.
